# Strict by default (non-negotiable)

**Canonical:** `docs/ecosystem/strict-by-default.md`

There is **no optional provability** by default. Mathematical proof, security, and performance gates run at **maximum** for every build/check. Users may **only relax** via **explicit** `li.toml` `[gates]` or **documented** env downgrades (for example `LI_BUILD_VERIFY_LEAN=0` for local dev with warning). Silence or omission never weakens a gate.

## Forbidden (agents)

- Suggesting `sorry`, `assume`, `unsafe`, or bare `cast` to “unblock” work
- `continue-on-error` on **CI OS jobs** (ubuntu / macOS / Windows) or treating platform CI as optional
- Skipping `requires` / `ensures` on new or changed `proc`
- Treating `lic check` as sufficient for ship — **`lic build`** is the certificate path
- Weakening `stdlib_seal`, removing CVE/exploit tests, or lowering bench thresholds without human approval + tracked issue
- Suggesting `git commit --no-verify`, `--no-verify`, or bypassing hooks/CI gates unless the user **explicitly** requests a documented downgrade
- Disabling proof “for speed” or “for LLM ergonomics”

## Required (agents)

- Contracts on every new/changed `proc`; loop specs where applicable
- Respect `check_stdlib_seal` and security harnesses when touching `std/` or policy
- Run relevant gates before claiming done (`li-tests`, `scripts/ci.sh`, stdlib coverage when applicable)
- Document explicit downgrades in `li.toml` `[gates]` — never implicit defaults-off

## Pillar order (unchanged)

Proof → easy syntax → fast execution. See `li-project.mdc`.
